Metamask ( @MetaMask ): Metamask is also a wallet I use, in my opinion it isn’t a million miles away from Trust wallet, but lacks the ability to store Bitcoin which is my largest asset holding.

This case will go down in history. Richard Heart has the attention of crypto and the world. 

There is more to this case than meets the eye. One may be mistaken in thinking this case is soley about Richard Heart, HEX, PulseChain and PulseX. Whoever wins this case will set legal precedent in crypto law for years to come. This means projects like Ethereum and such are at risk as well in the scenario that a bad precedent is set. It is evident that the government wants to gain control over things like crypto. Whether you were an investor in Ripple (XRP) or not, if you enjoy crypto freedom, then everyone ought to stand behind them, support them, and root for them. Recently they were victorious against the SEC in their multi year long lawsuit. The same applies to this case. If freedom of speech, & the right to transact is important to you - everyone in crypto should be rooting for Richard Heart. 

🔹𝐔𝐧𝐟𝐚𝐢𝐫 𝐓𝐚𝐫𝐠𝐞𝐭𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐟 𝐇𝐄𝐗 (𝐔𝐧𝐢𝐬𝐰𝐚𝐩)

Imagine you are Hayden Adams (the creator of Uniswap). You have just built a revolutionary 'decentralized' product where people can buy and sell crypto in a permissionless way. Richard Heart popularizes your product by telling all the Hexicans about your invention. In the process countless people in the HEX community end up getting the UNI airdrop. HEX becomes responsible for some of the highest amount of volume and activity on-chain helping your project and spreading the word. Yesterday, Uniswap marked HEX as an "unsupported asset". For lack of better terms, Uniswap single handedly spit on Richard Heart and HEX for helping them out in the early days. To make matters worse they consider themselves to be decentralized, and yet specifically target HEX. What's your problem Hayden Adams, do you dislike Richard Heart? Do you dislike HEX investors? Do you not believe in decentralization? This is simply an attack, shame on Uniswap. Uniswap has not acted when there were obvious scams and rugpulls, but specifically targets HEX today. 

🔹𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐫𝐝 𝐇𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐭

As an outsider it is very easy to dislike or not understand someone like Richard Heart. Why do I say this? Because I thought he was a scammer and I didn't trust him at first. Imagine someone tuning in for the first time and seeing a man with designer cloths twerking talking about crypto. This typically isn't the type of person you'd want to take seriously. However, if you take the time to dig deeper you will be shocked. In my opinion Richard Heart is one of the brighest minds in crypto who really cares about the small guys as well as our primary basic rights of freedom. In specific the freedom of speech and the right to transact are very relevant to this case. Richard Heart is the type of person where if you just listen for ten minutes, you will gain a wealth of knowledge and perspectives that you may have never thought of. How do I know this? I've spent countless hours watching his highly engaging videos. I am not sure whether the SEC underestimates the wit of Richard Heart, but I believe he is easily top three best to represent crypto. 

🔹𝐖𝐡𝐲 𝐝𝐨𝐞𝐬 𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐫𝐝 𝐇𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐭 𝐭𝐰𝐞𝐫𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐝𝐞𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐞𝐫 𝐜𝐥𝐨𝐭𝐡𝐬?!

Simply put - outrage marketing. Every action is strategic and surgical. In his older videos he has mentioned that he would wear a black t-shirt and speak his mind. Unfortunately this wasn't enough to get the proper amount of attention and eyes to do what he always wanted to accomplish. One of his goals was to make the best crypto built for the greatest price appreciation the world had ever seen. He was very successful in business before crypto, and even mined BTC blocks for cents back in the early days of Bitcoin. It's not about the money for him - his ultimate goal is legacy, glory, but most importantly love from his peers. 

I have tracked down 6+ older clips of Richard admitting that the stuff he does and wears is completely ridiculous. It's just about getting as many eyes as possible, then for those who stick around educating and teaching them about stuff that actually matters. To put into perspective how effective this tactic is, Richard single handedly tripled his Twitter follower count in the midst of the bear market. Plenty of clips and memes were created in the process - genius marketing. 

What I'm trying to say is the guy in designer isn't Richard Heart at all. Unfortunately that's what gets peoples attention, and he is the type of person to do whatever it takes to accomplish his goals. Months ago he has pivoted to being "humble". This was the real Richard Heart all along. I totally understand why some people dislike him, but I don't think they have met the real Richard.

This Theory calls tops and bottoms with a +/- 21 day accuracy and tells us what happens in each given year

Tops = +/- 21 days from Nov 28th end of red year (red dots)

Bottoms = +/- 21 days from Nov 28th beginning of green year (green dots)

The model starts on the day of the first halving, Nov 28th 2012.

Cycles have formed in between each date of Nov 28th.

Green year (Accumulation) = Bitcoin forms a bottom at the beginning of the year +/- 28 days from Nov 28th. This is the year of the best cycle buying prices, and the best time to accumulate. 

Price also moves towards the median price. (half of previous ATH). This is the first price that can be predicted labeled with blue lines, and their blue dot when price touches it.

Blue Year (Preparation for New ATHs) = Bitcoin spends time around the blue line (median), and then makes an advance towards new ATHs (small red line).

Price makes its cycle top +/- 21 days from Nov 28th at the end of the year.

Orange Year (Bear Market) = After becoming over-valuated at the cycle high, Bitcoin moves to undervaluation. On this scale, this has always been at a 44-degree descent. We can then find the next cycle bottom price using this measurement, which will come at the end of the year.

Bitcoin Spot ETFs are potentially VERY BAD for security, long term.

Let me explain something:

Bitcoin (the network) currently pays 6.25 $BTC (the token or coin) every ~10 minutes, which then gets distributed by mining pools 99% of the time.

(it has been REALLY HARD to win a full Bitcoin block by "solo mining" for a long time)

In the year 2140, Bitcoin will experience a final halving event. 

But if you look at the inflation chart below then you should see the practical reality: 

Bitcoin could stop being profitable to mine based on the block reward alone MUCH sooner than that.

What helps maintain profitability?

Fees.

Bottom-Line-Up-Front (BLUF) is that as the block reward decreases, ONE of the biggest recent factors in Bitcoin's economic incentive for SECURITY ("mining") is fees.

Transactions generate fees.

Minting ordinal inscriptions generate fees.

On-chain DeFi (sites like @NOWPFinance) generates fees.

All of these fees are added to the current 6.25 BTC payout to give incentive to the world to absolutely CRUSH the hashrate of Bitcoin, and spend an increasing amount of effort into solving more hashes.

Know what DOESN'T give Bitcoin's layer 1 network fees?

Off-chain orderbooks.

CEX's, escrows, and (taps glass) ETFs.

All of these remove transaction volume from Bitcoin's layer 1, which 100% DELETES the built-in fee incentive.

"But Seth, an ETF will usher in mass adoption!"

OK, so you want decreased security funding, and you want it AT SCALE?

(BTW this is the same fundamental problem of Lightning Network or @ElonMusk's previous offer to shift DOGE to proof of stake)

So, the more adoption a Bitcoin Spot ETF receives, the LESS SECURE the native asset- Bitcoin- becomes.

"But Seth, isn't that priced in? Won't Bitcoin's price appreciation make the decreased fees palatable to miners?"

No.

Because it will substantially decrease the number of fees actually paid (fully DELETING the majority of them) and in ways we can't forecast very well.

Bitcoin security has absolutely gone through some rough patches- MANY entities have folded/gone bankrupt over building too much mining infrastructure too soon.

I LIKE the idea of price discovery & appreciation.
I WANT to be financially free because of my good habits in crypto.

But, like most people, I NEED for Bitcoin to be sustainably secure more than I need it to make me accidentally rich.
